<TEXT>
the christmas freeze that hit major vegetable 
areas of the south is responsible for a sharp increase in the 
agriculture departments price index for raw farm products 
according to preliminary figures 
department officials said wednesday the overall index received 
by farmers rose 27 percent from december to january leaving the 
monthly average also 27 percent above the yearago level 
higher prices for tomatoes lettuce and broilers mostly were 
responsible for the increase from december the departments 
agricultural statistics board said in its preliminary report 
tomato prices more than doubled due to short supplies brought 
on by the freeze in florida in december the report said 
lettuce prices were nearly double for the same reason 
commercial vegetables as a group were up 68 percent from 
december and 32 percent from a year ago 
lower prices were reported for soybeans strawberries and 
oranges 
milk prices at the farm which had risen to record levels late 
last year were unchanged in january department dairy economists 
have forecast milk prices would level off this year 
prices paid by farmers to meet expenses meanwhile were up 11 
percent from october the previous reading and averaged 29 
percent above a year ago the report said the prices paid 
index is revised every three months 
the report said prices for feeder cattle and calves feeder 
pigs diesel fuel and lp gas were up from october 
department economists say the net cash income of farmers in 1990 
may be in the range of 52 billion to 57 billion compared with 
about 53 billion in 1989 
net cash income is the money nationally that farmers have left 
from gross cash income during a calendar year after deducting cash 
expenses it includes government payments and proceeds from crops 
grown previously but sold during the year 
in another method taking into account changes in inventories 
depreciation and other allowances during a calendar year shows that 
1990 net farm income may be in the range of 44 billion to 49 
billion compared with 48 billion last year 
consumer food prices are estimated by department economists to 
have risen about 57 percent this year the sharpest rise since 
1981 they project food prices may rise 3 percent to 5 percent in 
1990 
based on the preliminary figures the january price index for 
livestock and poultry was unchanged from december but averaged 76 
percent more than a year ago 
crop prices overall rose 63 percent from december but 
averaged 43 percent below a year ago the sharp rise in the price 
of commercial vegetables caused most of the increase from december 
the report said 
the fruit index dropped 93 percent from december and was 98 
percent below a year earlier 
all fruit prices used in the index were down from last month 
except for apples and lemons which were up slightly the report 
said oranges and strawberries had the largest downward influence 
on the index 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a new oilseed lobbying group has urged 
legislation to guarantee farmers a larger choice in what they 
produce under federal crop programs 
the oilseed council of america said wednesday that genuine 
planting flexibility would help solve a decline in the 
competitiveness of the us oilseed industry oilseeds are led by 
soybeans but also include cottonseed sunflowers and canola 
lowell wilson of primghar iowa cochairman of the council 
said current commodity programs have dramatically reduced acreage 
planted to oilseeds by requiring producers to plant commodities 
supported by target prices to protect crop program base acreages 
used to compute benefits 
wilson said there is genuine planting flexibility when federal 
programs are neutral in their effect on farmers planting decisions 
according to a study released in washington by the council 
demand for protein meal and oil produced when oilseeds are crushed 
is growing at the rate of 4 percent a year world trade in oilseeds 
and their products the report said has increased twice as fast as 
trade in wheat and feed grains 
despite the growth the study reported the us share of global 
oilseed production has dropped to 24 percent from 39 percent six 
years ago and that the us share of oilseed trade has declined to 
45 percent from 75 percent 
floyd anderson of bismarck nd president of the national 
sunflowerseed association and cochairman of the council said 
planting flexibility would let farmers take advantage of the world 
demand for oilseeds by basing planting decisions on market 
situations as well as natural factors 
the formation of the group coincides with moves in congress to 
write new farm legislation to replace the 1985 law which expires 
at the end of the 1990 crop season 
but anderson said in a statement the council does not advocate 
any specific programs and that there are a number of policy 
approaches that will give producers genuine planting 
flexibility and continue farm income protection 
</TEXT>
