<TEXT>
a coalition of labor and social organizations 
called on taxpayers today to stage their own boston tea party and 
mail congress envelopes of crumbs to protest president bushs 
proposed capital gains tax cut 
the theme of the campaign would be a capital gains tax cut is 
a crummy idea according to citizens for tax justice 
the nonprofit coalition of labor citizen and social groups 
played a major role in passage of the 1986 tax overhaul and 
includes organizations claiming 20 million members 
restoring the capital gains loophole would be cake for the 
rich but crumbs for the rest of us robert s mcintyre director 
of citizens for tax justice said in launching the campaign 
if the campaign catches on members of congress could expect to 
be swamped with cookie remnants and letters declaring while 
youre giving the wealthy the whole pie youre leaving most 
americans with nothing but crumbs so you can have my crumbs back 
because im tired of paying higher taxes to give tax cuts to the 
rich 
bush has proposed that capital gains profits from the sale of 
real estate stock and other investments be given preferential 
tax treatment compared with wages and other incomes 
the plan the president outlined monday would when fully 
effective in 1993 tax only 70 percent of the profits from the sale 
of assets owned three years or more 80 percent of assets owned 
more than two years and 90 percent of profits from the sale of 
property held at least one year present law taxes 100 percent of 
gains 
bush said a tax break for capital gains would encourage 
investment that would create jobs and make us businesses more 
competitive abroad 
the house passed a capital gains tax cut last year but 
democratic leaders were able to kill it in the senate even though 
most senators favored it 
opponents say 80 percent of the benefits from a capital gains 
cut would go to people with incomes over 100000 a year they 
contend it would worsen the budget deficit and lead to the undoing 
of the 1986 tax overhaul 
the coalition expects to distribute more than 10 million 
brochures and addressed envelopes in february and march in an 
attempt to defeat the capital gains reduction 
in contending that only the truly rich would profit from a 
capital gains cut the campaign letter cites bush and hotel owner 
leona helmsley who was convicted of tax evasion as examples 
mrs helmsley and her husband harry saved 38 million in taxes 
in 1983 through 1985 because of an earlier capital gains break the 
letter says in 1986 bush saved 129000 in taxes because of his 
capital gains 
the 58 organizations sponsoring the protest include the aflcio 
childrens defense fund consumer federation of america and an arm 
of the united church of christ 
