<TEXT>
labor department officers who police the 
nations pension system are poorly equipped for their job says 
the departments inspector general in questioning plans to add 100 
agents to the unit 
the officers dont have the mentality and the learning curve 
to know how to look and where to look for racketeers acting 
inspector general raymond maria said wednesday before a house panel 
studying the nations 17 trillion private pension system 
these types of complex cases generally require tips 
informants and the execution of search warrants maria said 
adding the departments officers are poorly equipped for these 
tasks 
but david ball who heads the departments pension benefits and 
welfare administration said those agents have closed 8268 pension 
investigations in the past five years and recovered 480 million 
the house education and labor subcommittee on labormanagement 
relations is studying enforcement of the employee retirement income 
security act passed in 1974 to protect retirees from abuses in 
their pensions plans 
maria and the labor department have been feuding over the 
departments handling of pension investigations 
maria who will not be permanently named to the inspector 
generals post has insisted the department improperly relies on 
civil instead of criminal remedies and that problems with the 
pension system rival those blamed for the savings and loan crisis 
ball called the comparison to the sampl crisis inflammatory 
rhetoric its like shouting fire in a crowded theater 
ball said the pension system with assets that have grown from 
290 billion to 17 trillion over the past 15 years has never 
been healthier he said there has been no evidence of widespread 
fraud in benefit plans 
after the hearing maria said he was skeptical of department 
plans to add 100 enforcement officers without a change in the way 
investigations are pursued 
if you dont have a sound game plan why add more players 
maria said 
the labor departments budget request for fiscal 1991 calls for 
increasing from 200 to 300 the number of pension enforcement 
ball said the addition of 100 enforcement officers would let the 
agency conduct an additional 1000 investigations he defended the 
departments pursuit of civil remedies and said criminal 
investigations are turned over to the justice department where he 
said they belong 
using what will be one of his last appearances before congress 
as acting inspector general president bush is expected to 
nominate a replacement within a week or so maria said department 
enforcement officers have not been trained to investigate 
professional racketeers 
maria also renewed his criticism of a justice department ruling 
that curtailed the investigative powers of inspectors general 
the ruling prohibited the inspectors general from launching 
their own investigations of alleged violations of agency 
regulations in essence the ruling said the departments themselves 
were responsible for such enforcement and that the role of 
inspectors general was to investigate and analyze the departments 
efforts 
maria wants congress to pass legislation giving inspectors 
general broader powers and jurisdictions 
