<TEXT>
the prosecutor in the nations longest 
criminal trial says it will be an uphill fight to convict mcmartin 
preschool molestation defendant raymond buckey at a new trial but 
the case must be resolved 
district attorney ira reiner insisted that neither politics nor 
public pressure influenced his decision wednesday to pursue charges 
in the 6yearold case 
this is not a political matter and it is not going to be 
treated as such said reiner a candidate for california attorney 
general in junes election 
buckey and his mother were acquitted jan 18 of 52 molestation 
counts after a 33month trial the jury deadlocked on 12 
molestation charges and one conspiracy count against buckey 
buckey 31 will be retried on those charges 
this case has gone on for many years reiner said it must 
be resolved 
prosecutors said at least one child who did not testify at the 
first trial might testify at the second but conceded they might 
lose as witnesses one or two of the five children named in the 13 
counts the judge has suggested dropping some of the counts to 
speed the march 9 retrial 
if convicted on all 13 charges buckey could draw no more than 
36 years in prison reiner said but most defendants serve about 
half of their sentences and buckey already has been jailed with 
bail for five years the equivalent of a 10year sentence 
buckey said he was surprised by reiners decision but expected 
acquittal 
i believe the das decision was based on political pressure 
from a few vocal parents of children not involved in this trial 
rather than jurors leaning toward acquittal he said 
in the two weeks since the acquittals parents whose children 
attended the nowdefunct mcmartin nursery school mounted a strident 
campaign for a new trial they appeared on tv talk shows called 
news conferences and recruited politicians who vowed to take the 
case out of reiners hands if he failed to follow through 
reiner said his prime consideration was the feelings of parents 
and alleged victims who now range from age 11 to 14 
this is a positive step for us said marymae cioffi a 
mcmartin parent who led the campaign to retry buckey im going 
to run home and tell my kids we get another chance 
reiner said there remain serious evidentiary problems which 
he blamed on his predecessor robert philibosian 
this is an uphill battle theres no question about that 
reiner said 
the former district attorney has said he takes no responsibility 
for the case which he initially filed in 1984 with seven 
defendants under investigation 
five had charges dismissed after an 18month preliminary 
hearing only buckey and his mother peggy mcmartin buckey 63 
stood trial 
the trial was the longest and costliest in us history 
taxpayers have spent over 13 million on the case so far 
superior court judge william pounders said the facts in the 
remaining 13 counts mitigate in favor of a long second trial 
he said he hoped the charges could be scoped down to shorten 
the proceedings 
pounder urged a swift start because the range of emotions is 
very high there are a lot of people still sitting in agony we 
should seek an end to this as soon as possible 
buckeys attorney danny davis filed a motion denouncing the 
judge and seeking his removal for bias against him and buckey 
another judge will have to rule on that motion which could cause 
delays 
