<TEXT>
the new national geographic map of the soviet 
union is a more political document that gives a primer of russian 
annexation over the centuries as well as clues to possible future 
troubles the chief cartographer says 
there are still 15 republics and they are still part of the 
ussr said john b garver jr chief cartographer of the 
national geographic society 
but we are very excited at being able to put out a map when 
there is a possibility of change he said referring to unrest 
and secessionist movements in several soviet republics 
the new map doesnt show the latest protests and battles 
involving soviet nationalities but its charts graphs text and 
historical inserts can help readers follow and even predict trouble 
for the kremlin 
next to the soviet baltic republics mapmakers added a note in 
red ink the united states does not recognize the 1940 
incorporation of estonia latvia and lithuania 
popular fronts in those republics are agitating to leave the 
soviet union against the wishes of soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev 
adjacent to the kuril islands in the pacific the map says 
formerly part of and still claimed by japan the disputed islands 
kunashir iturup shikotan and the habomais have been held by the 
soviet union since 1945 
tokyo has balked at improving relations with moscow until the 
two settle the issue of the islands which are occupied by soviet 
troops 
such disputes are grist in the mill of garver a former army 
colonel and west point professor who is helping shift the focus of 
national geographic magazine to current events 
the flip side of the new map tells an even more graphic 
political tale 
we did away with the pictures and replaced them with a map of 
russian historical annexation over the centuries its sort of a 
primer said garver if you read the text and examine the map 
you see that the soviet union has expanded mostly by conquest 
since the 14th century 
the map shows that over the centuries the princes and czars of 
ancient moscow gobbled up adjoining territories in europe siberia 
and central asia and that at the close of world war ii the 
soviets occupied eastern europe and annexed parts of poland 
czechoslovakia and romania 
a demographic map shows that ethnic russian colonists spread 
east from moscow and bar graphs depict some trends from the 1989 
soviet census that are unsettling for the kremlin 
the entry under soviet tadzhikistan says that if current 
trends continue the ussr could be a predominantly muslim 
country within a century trouble for a government that is 
officially atheist 
the bar graphs garver said show that the turkish central 
asian and islamic populations are increasing the russian and other 
european populations are increasing at a much slower pace 
the map took a year to complete in part because of the need to 
reconfirm the location of the 5000 cities lakes rivers and 
mountains that dot the 86 million square miles of the soviet 
union thats more than twice the area of the united states with 
36 million square miles 
among the most striking changes in the new map is the shrinking 
of the aral sea down 40 percent since the last national geographic 
map of the soviet union was produced in 1977 
the amu darya and syr darya rivers that once fed the aral no 
longer flow into it because their waters have been diverted to 
irrigate cotton fields 
the falling water level of the aral moved it from fourth to 
sixth place among the largest lakes of the world according to the 
february edition of national geographic magazine which described 
it as one of the globes worst ecological disasters 
</TEXT>
