<TEXT>
a study today raises the possibility of 
populationwide screening for carriers of cystic fibrosis but some 
worry about what will happen to parents who ignore the knowledge 
that they can pass on the disease 
making the test mandatory has the potential for grave 
danger warned dr harvey r colten of washington university 
even voluntary screening programs carry considerable economic and 
social risk 
cystic fibrosis is the most common fatal genetic disease of 
young americans it occurs most frequently among whites striking 
about one of every 2500 white newborns in the united states 
for the first time scientists can delve into grownups genes 
and spot those likely to bear children with the inherited illness 
while the test is still too crude for routine use doctors believe 
that within a year it will be able to detect 95 percent of all 
carriers of cystic fibrosis 
people for years have realized that if we had a good carrier 
test for cystic fibrosis there would be the potential to test 
everyone before reproduction to see if they were a carrier or 
not said dr arthur l beaudet of baylor college of medicine in 
houston the evidence is at hand that such a carrier test will 
soon be available 
beaudet described the results of the currently available 
screening test in a report in the new england journal of medicine 
his team found that it can identify 76 percent of all carriers 
one in 25 white americans carries one copy of the cystic 
fibrosis gene they are healthy but if they marry another carrier 
there is a 1in4 chance that their children will have cystic 
fibrosis 
last summer drs lapchee tsui of the hospital for sick 
children in toronto and francis s collins of the university of 
michigan pinpointed the genetic error responsible for most cases of 
cystic fibrosis the latest study looked at what happened when 
doctors screened people for this single defect 
scientists at about 40 labs around the world are cooperating to 
track down the half dozen or so other mutations within the gene 
that also can cause the disease collins predicted that the 
mutations will be identified within the next year then doctors 
should be able to offer highly accurate screening tests 
specialists hope that adults will use the test results for 
family planning if couples learn that both are carriers some 
might decide to adopt rather than run the risk of having a child 
with cystic fibrosis others might opt to have artificial 
insemination with sperm from an anonymous donor who is not a 
carrier 
if they decide to have a pregnancy the test can be performed on 
the fetus if the fetus turns out to have the disease parents can 
then decide whether to have the baby or to get an abortion 
the disease causes a variety of symptoms including abnormal 
mucous secretion that results in lung infections while doctors can 
ease many of the symptoms and extend lives there is no treatment 
for the underlying disease collins noted that if everyone in the 
united states gets the screening test it will turn up 8 million 
americans who carry the cystic fibrosis gene 
if this program is successful every one of them deserves to 
sit down with someone and find out what that means he said we 
dont by a long shot have the means to do that physicians are 
uncomfortable with that role and there arent enough genetic 
counselors to do the job 
in an editorial in the journal colten raised the possibility 
that insurance companies might refuse to pay the bills of children 
with cystic fibrosis if their parents knew before the pregnancy 
that they were carriers 
dr henry dorkin of new england medical center in boston said 
that while he supports widespread screening carriers should be 
allowed to make their own decisions about whether to have children 
we have to give people as much information as possible about 
the risks and pitfalls that lie ahead of them he said and 
after informing them we should support their decision whatever it 
is 
other questions involve at what age people should be screened 
and whether the tests should be routinely offered to nonwhites 
who have a much lower risk of cystic fibrosis 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

