<TEXT>
one of the largest plastics producers in 
the united states unveiled plans to open the nations first 
multimaterial comprehensive plastic recycling plant 
union carbide chemicals and plastics inc said wednesday the 
facility would be the first in the nation to recycle the ubiquitous 
plastic bags the plant also will recycle plastic beverage 
containers 
the recycling center is expected to open next year in converted 
space at the companys central new jersey manufacturing plant at 
piscataway 
the effort was praised by state officials and legislators but 
environmental groups were skeptical saying the recycling plans 
might be little more than a bid to keep plasticbanning lawmakers 
at bay 
union carbide officials said the project was aimed at making 
money as well as easing a nationwide garbage problem that is 
particularly acute in densely populated new jersey 
these cost a lot of money company vice president gordon 
mounts told a statehouse news conference as he gestured toward a 
display of plastic bags and containers we really dont believe 
we can use them just once 
only about 1 percent of the 60 billion pounds of plastic 
produced in the united states is being recycled now union carbide 
officials said the new plant will demonstrate that plastic can be 
reused on a far wider scale 
environmentalists said readily recyclable glass and naturally 
degrading paper are better for the environment than plastic 
i dont doubt union carbide does want recycling but they 
are doing it as much for the public relations as for the 
profitability of the venture said lisa collaton a solid waste 
specialist for the washingtonbased group environmental action 
but assemblyman robert smith chairman of the lower houses 
environment committee said the effort appeared genuine and will 
dramatically change the approach government takes to the plastics 
problem 
he said theres now a real alternative to several state 
bills that propose restricting or banning plastic packaging though 
none have passed 
plastics industry officials say more than 350 legislative 
initiatives have been introduced at the federal state and local 
levels around the country to curb the use of nonrecyclable 
plastics 
the plants breakthrough union carbide officials said was its 
ability to accept plastic bags the socalled plastic films now 
are recycled in europe but not in the united states said keith 
atkins director of new business for the companys polyolefins 
division 
about 20 percent of the softdrink containers used in the 
country also are being recycled but the percentage is nowhere near 
as high with other types of plastic 
union carbide officials said the new plant would melt the bags 
down like other types of plastic the material will be fashioned 
into pellets to be sold to plastic packaging manufacturers 
the new plant will be able to handle 40 million pounds out of 
more than 1 billion pounds of plastic garbage generated in new 
jersey each year but company officials said their project at least 
would demonstrate that comprehensive and profitable plastic 
recycling is possible 
