<TEXT>
lawmakers have voted unanimously to 
declare namibia independent in midmarch ending the territorys 
status as the continents last colony after 75 years of south 
african rule 
leaders of the southwest africa peoples organization dominant 
in the constituent assembly said wednesday that march 21 was 
chosen unaninimously in part because the united nations recognizes 
it as the international day for the elimination of apartheid 
for many years south africas apartheid policies of racial 
segregation were imposed on namibias blacks 
south africa agreed to grant independence to namibia also known 
as southwest africa under a regional peace treaty more than 
6000 united nations military and civilian personnel have been 
supervising the process since april 1989 
the 72member assembly this week has been debating each article 
of a democratic westernstyle constitution and has agreed on all 
the major principles it is likely to formally approve the document 
on friday or monday 
the assembly on wednesday eliminated a provision that would have 
allowed for detention without trial under some circumstances swapo 
favored keeping the provision but agreed to drop the measure when 
the opposition parties objected 
also a proposal that guarantees fundamental rights even during 
times of war and states of emergency was approved 
all decisions on the constitution require a twothirds majority 
the document has declaration of fundamental rights including 
freedom of movement speech and a free press it also envisions a 
multiparty democracy regular elections an independent judiciary 
and an executive president limited to two fiveyear terms 
leftistoriented swapo which waged a 23year bush war against 
south african rule captured 41 seats in the assembly and will form 
the first government swapos leader sam nujoma is expected to be 
the countarys first president 
the democratic turnhalle alliance a multiracial coalition that 
favors a free enterprise economy has 21 seats the 10 remaining 
seats are divided among five parties 
