nasa decided to replace a fuel 
turbopump in space shuttle atlantis but said the repairs probably 
will not delay the shuttles launch now set for feb 22 
technicians began the weeklong job of replacing the turbopump 
located in one of the spaceships three engines late wednesday 
according to conrad nagel who leads a nasa team readying atlantis 
for launch 
nagel said the repair work was not expected to interrupt flight 
preparations although the schedule is a little soft if things go 
well there shouldnt be any impact to the launch date nagel 
said 
atlantis is scheduled to carry a secret cargo into space for the 
department of defense the national aeronautics and space 
administration has not set an official launch date but the liftoff 
is targeted for feb 22 
the turbopump became a concern after the failure of an unrelated 
fuel pump duct during a routine pressure test at the engines 
manufacturer the rocketdyne division of rockwell international in 
canoga park calif 
the failure was in a titanium weld done outside the factory 
according to nagel an inflight failure could hinder the flow of 
fuel to the engine 
that lead us to inspect other such welds and this turbopump 
is suspect nagel said we dont think we have a problem with 
it but safety first 
nasas concern for safety also lead engineers to order the 
replacement of a seal in an ignition controller on one of atlantis 
two solidfuel booster rockets 
that work announced several days ago and planned for sunday 
was not expected to cause a launch delay either according to nagel 
postflight inspections of the reusable rockets used to boost 
columbia into space jan 9 showed a tiny void in an identical seal 
the void is located in a backup seal on a gasket attached to a 
device on the coneshaped portion of the rocket it was missed 
during tests at the boosters manufacturer thiokol corp in utah 
according to nagel 
you would be hard pressed to see it with the naked eye he 
said but technicians will replace the atlantis seal to be 
ultraconservative 
