<TEXT>
west germany would be dealt the hardest 
economic blow by the largescale us troop cuts in europe that 
president bush proposed in his state of the union speech 
bush proposed that us and soviet troops be reduced to 225000 
in europe down to 195000 in central europe because of the 
dizzying collapse of east bloc communist regimes 
about 250000 us servicemen are based in west germany alone 
with another 55000 in britain italy turkey and greece 
west german foreign minister hansdietrich genscher called 
bushs proposal an important step forward west german defense 
minister gerhard stoltenberg called it a balanced combination of 
disarmament policy and unequivocal recognition of the wests 
defense readiness and alliance solidarity 
the colognebased german economics institute reported in a july 
study that west germany earns 5 billion a year from us military 
expenditures it warned that a troop pullout would mean economic 
collapse for regions that are heavily dependent on the american 
presence 
an extensive analysis of the us bases was undertaken because 
of the growing public tendency to see american troops as a burden 
institute director for economic and scientific affairs otto vogel 
said at the time 
there has been increasing support in recent months for troop 
cuts as a way to reduce tensions in europe and move the german 
states closer to reunification now that the communists in east 
germany no longer have a monopoly on power 
east germany is the kremlins most critical military ally and 
about 400000 of the 565000 soviet troops in europe are stationed 
in the country 
the kremlin does not want to lose its frontline bases in east 
germany but it has indicated it could accept a neutral state 
communist premier hans modrow was in moscow meeting with kremlin 
leaders this week but there was no word on whether they discussed 
the extremely sensitive topic of reducing soviet troops in east 
germany 
as they move away from four decades of kremlin domination 
poland hungary and czechoslovakia are pushing for the complete 
withdrawal of soviet troops from their territory none of the three 
are considered nearly as crucial to soviet security as east germany 
west germany is under pressure to remain in nato and keep troops 
as part of its commitment to the western defense alliance the 
troops however are an obstacle to reunification 
last may bush proposed a 275000 ceiling on us and on soviet 
forces in central europe and said negotiations to reach that goal 
should be wrapped up within a year 
before now bush has said he would not support further cuts 
until the current talks were wrapped up but a senior 
administration official said events were running ahead of the 
negotiations 
