<TEXT>
a soviet cosmonaut took a spin in space thursday 
on a special motorcycle designed for rescuing spacemen and 
officials said the vehicles maiden journey outside the orbiting 
station mir was a success 
flight engineer alexander a serebrov rode the cycle as far as 
30 yards away from the giant station while mission commander 
alexander s viktorenko stayed at mirs exit hatch and monitored 
the cycles operations 
soviet tv interrupted its regular programs several times during 
the day for special coverage of the fivehour spacewalk live 
pictures showed serebrov 45 attached to a tether anchored on mir 
as he prepared to ride the cycle 
a taped report showed the cosmonaut with his left side in the 
sun and right in shadow slowly riding away from mir his image 
growing smaller 
a correspondent emphasized the drama of floating in space while 
connected to mir only by a rope he told viewers in the nighttime 
newscast vremya it was risky and dangerous work 
but tass said the results of the 30yard test ride and three 
fiveyard trips were good its easy operation and good 
maneuverability were confirmed the news agency said further 
tests are planned monday 
its not much of a motorcycle by earth standards it actually 
looks more like a floating armchair weighing 485 pounds with 32 
motors 
the cycle is designed for repairing satellites and rescuing 
spacemen in distress it can rotate and move to a maximum distance 
of 50 yards away from mir 
the device formally known as the cosmonaut movement system is 
similar to the manned maneuvering unit that us space shuttle 
astronauts have used soviet officials say 
the cycle was delivered to mir on dec 6 after two delays it 
originally was scheduled to blast off last april but it wasnt 
ready and a second launching planned for september was scrapped 
because of problems with its electronic docking system 
the 20ton mir was designed to be permanently manned and was 
host to a record yearlong flight by two cosmonauts in 1988 but it 
was unexpectedly mothballed in april because the module and another 
addon were not ready and keeping a crew aboard would have cost 
money when legislators and ordinary soviets were demanding that 
space rubles be spent on earth 
the fourmonth vacancy was only the second time since mir was 
launched in february 1986 that it was unmanned 
mir already is joined with kvant an astrophysics laboratory 
viktorenko and serebrov have been aboard mir since september and 
are scheduled to be replaced later this month by another crew 
</TEXT>
