<DOCNO> AP900201-0154 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
firefighters police officers and health 
workers exposed to the aids virus on the job can get free doses of 
the drug azt in a pioneering program in one california county 
officials said thursday 
orange county officials said they believe it is the first 
organized program nationwide to offer emergency workers access to 
the aidsfighting drug 
health care workers are not the only people who get exposed 
to aids said dr tom prendergast chief epidemiologist for the 
county south of los angeles paramedics police and others who risk 
exposure also should have use of azt he said thursday 
the program implemented in september was discussed by county 
aids coordinator penny weismuller at an aids conference wednesday 
under the program five public safety workers took azt 
immediately after potential exposure to the virus ms weismuller 
said animal studies indicate that infection may be prevented if 
the drug is administered within 96 hours of exposure she said 
the therapy was suggested in august by researchers with the 
national institutes of health and the university of california san 
francisco who have developed azt programs for their healthcare 
workers 
the program is intended for workers involved in incidents which 
would put them at serious risk of exposure if the other person 
turned out to be infected with aids ms weismuller said examples 
would be cases where the worker is actually stabbed by a needle or 
directly exposed to blood 
the first person to take azt under the orange county program was 
a police officer who cut his arm while scuffling with a man ms 
weismuller said blood from a cut in the mans scalp dripped 
directly into a wound the officer sustained during the fight 
the city called us right away which was good because we knew 
this suspect and knew he was aids virus positive ms 
weismuller said the officer took the drug for the recommended four 
weeks and continues to test negative for the virus she added 
the four other workers given azt took it for less than four 
days she said they stopped using the drug after the people they 
were exposed to tested negative for the virus 
anaheim fire chief jeff bowman said thursday the azt program 
must be viewed cautiously 
im very much in favor of it but its not a cureall 
bowman said there are concerns about azt side effects which 
include nausea and headaches and about longterm consequences such 
as cancer he said 
the best thing is prevention bowman said noting that masks 
and gloves intended to prevent exposure to the aids virus have 
become standard gear for paramedics 
the most common type of exposure occurs when workers handling 
needles contaminated with blood from an aids patient accidentally 
prick themselves officials said 
when youre working a car accident in the middle of a street 
at night needles are flying everywhere bowman said 
orange county pays for the azt therapy but asks reimbursement 
from cities or workercompensation plans ms weismuller said the 
drug costs about 200 for the monthlong period 
only about 4 percent of those who are directly exposed to the 
aids virus on the job develop the disease said julie gerberding a 
uc researcher 
orange county population about 22 million had an aids rate 
through november 1989 of 546 cases per 100000 population 
prendergast said that compares to a national rate of 453 cases 
per 100000 he said 
</TEXT>
