<TEXT>
treasury secretary nicholas brady on thursday 
said he was satisfied with the achievements of the administrations 
muchcriticized third world debt strategy and predicted more 
success in the coming year 
brady said that the first agreement with mexico would be 
signed this sunday and he predicted that another agreement would be 
finalized by midmonth with the philippines 
he said that an agreement with costa rica was expected before 
the end of march and that later in the year debt reduction packages 
could be reached with two of the third worlds largest debtors 
venezuela and brazil 
i am very pleased with the progress that we have made in the 
attempts to alleviate third world debt brady said in answer to a 
question before the senate budget committee i think a pattern is 
beginning to emerge whereby we can deal with these problems 
the administrations debt strategy often referred to as the 
brady debt plan was unveiled by the treasury secretary in march 
1989 it had an initial goal of cutting the commercial bank debt of 
39 countries chiefly in latin america by 20 percent 
the plan envisioned using incentives supplied by the 
international monetary fund and the world bank to entice commercial 
banks to voluntarily forgive a portion of their old debt in 
exchange for guarantees that the reduced debt would be repaid 
critics however said the deal with mexico considered a test 
case for the brady plan produced debt relief far below what had 
been hoped and that other countries were even further from reaching 
agreements with commercial banks 
but brady said the debt plan while setting enormous goals 
had been working well in producing a variety of debt reduction 
packages that will soon be signed 
starting from scratch this past year we now have some of the 
machinery down working rather smoothly so that we dont have to 
reinvent the wheel every time we do one of these transactions 
he said 
on another topic brady acknowledged that the administrations 
proposal to cut the tax on corporate profits envisoned that the 
measure would be enacted by march 1 1990 a goal that senate 
budget committee chairman james sasser dtenn called totally 
unrealistic 
if it does not go into effect until later in the year it will 
reduce by a significant amount the 49 billion in revenues the 
administration is anticipating receiving from persons selling off 
their assets to take advantage of the lower tax rate the 49 
billion represents the biggest revenue measure in the 
administrations 1991 budget which was unveiled on monday 
sasser said that enactment of the capital gains cut would not 
come before september or october at the earliest 
brady said that a delay in enacting the proposal would cut into 
the revenues the administration is counting on to reduce the budget 
deficit and we will have to figure out a way to make up the 
shortfall 
brady refused to answer a reporters question after the hearing 
about where the administration might look to make up the lost 
revenue 
asked by reporters about repeated rumors that he is considering 
resigning brady termed such reports absolutely untrue and 
compared the rumors to recent resignation rumors involving soviet 
president mikhail gorbachev 
i am delighted to be included in the same category as general 
secretary gorbachev brady said 
