the air force has specified some 24000 
civilian workers holding sensitive jobs as eligible for random drug 
testing and expects to begin the tests by the end of the month the 
pentagon announced thursday 
were looking at testing approximately 6000 employees per 
year said an air force spokesman maj lou figueroa 
employees who test positive will not be allowed to remain in 
their jobs and will be referred to a substanceabuse counseling 
program they will also be subject to appropriate disciplinary 
action which could include a written reprimand suspension or 
firing a pentagon statement said 
the program is designed to ensure employees refrain from using 
illegal drugs on or off duty and also will include applicants 
for the posts deemed to be sensitive the pentagon statement said 
all of the tests will screen for marijuana or cocaine use tests 
for amphetamines opiates and pcp can be ordered the spokesman 
said 
the air force has some 566000 military personnel and 260000 
civilian employees all activeduty military personnel have been 
subject to random drug tests since 1981 
the air force has begun bargaining with the affected labor 
unions on the matter the statement said 
the program is designed to affect those civlians occupying or 
applying for positions that directly relate to the public health 
and safety the protection of life and property law enforcement 
and national security the statement said 
example of those positions include firefighters police medical 
personnel criminal investigators air traffic controllers 
aircraft mechanics employees associated with nuclear weapons or 
those with access to sensitive national security information the 
statement said 
all other civilians could be subject to testing if there is a 
reasonable suspicion of illegal drug use or following 
accidents safety mishaps or as a followup to a rehabilitation 
program for illegal drug use 
figueroa said such a suspicion could be based upon such things 
as the direct observation of drug use or possession by an employee 
abnormal conduct or erratic behavior or arrest or conviction of a 
drugrelated offense 
the army has been testing its civilian workforce since 1986 but 
the navy isnt conducting random tests of its civilian employees 
because of a lawsuit 
pentagon spokesman william caldwell said civilians in the office 
of secretary of defense have been randomly tested for drugs since 
april 1989 
</TEXT>
