<TEXT>
attorney general dick thornburgh asked a 
special court thursday to appoint an independent counsel to 
investigate allegations of criminal wrongdoing by former housing 
secretary samuel r pierce jr and other former federal housing 
officials 
the independent counsel if appointed would be asked to probe 
allegations that pierce and other department of housing and urban 
development officials may have violated federal criminal law in 
the administration of the hud moderate income rehabilitation 
program 
in a letter to the house judiciary committee thornburgh said 
the special counsel was being sought to investigate allegations 
that pierce and other hud officials may have committed the crime 
of conspiracy to defraud the united states or any other crime in 
administering that program between 1984 and 1988 
thornburghs formal application to a special court cited reports 
of a widespread perception among developers and local officials 
that funds were being disbursed in a disproportionate amounts to 
projects backed by prominent republicans acting as consultants or 
by former hud officials 
but the attorney general said he found no reasonable grounds 
to believe that further investigation is warranted of allegations 
that pierce lied during congressional testimony when questioned 
last may about political favoritism in the awarding of hud grants 
thornburgh signalled his reluctance to use the independent 
counsel law saying he had very little latitutde in making this 
determination i must apply to the court for an indepedent counsel 
unless i can determine that there are no reasonable grounds to 
believe that further investigation is warranted 
the attorney generals application to the special division of 
the us circuit court of appeals for the district of columbia was 
released by the department after the threejudge panel approved 
thornburghs motion to make it public 
pierces successor at hud jack kemp promised to cooperate with 
the investigation once the appointment is made by the special 
court 
this is a tragic situation for all involved kemp said in a 
statement however the department will provide whatever 
cooperation and assistance is required for full and fair 
disposition of this matter 
robert plotkin one of pierces lawyers said we continue to 
believe that mr pierce has not violated any federal laws and we 
are confident that at the conclusion of an independent counsel 
investigation that will be determined 
the attorney generals move came after the justice departments 
criminal division conducted a preliminary inquiry into allegations 
that pierce lied to a house subcommittee when questioned last 
spring about political favoritism in the awarding of grants during 
his tenure in the reagan administration 
the preliminary investigation was triggered last fall by the 19 
democratic members of the house judiciary committee who requested 
appointment of an independent counsel to investigate allegations of 
political favoritism and perjury by pierce 
thornburgh an outspoken critic of the special prosecutor law 
said his decision to seek appointment of an independent counsel was 
compelled by the severe restrictions on his ability to conduct an 
investigation that were placed upon him by statute 
a determination that no further investigation is warranted is 
virtually forclosed despite a review of voluminous 
information compiled by the hud inspector general the house 
subcommittee and justice department interviews with hud officials 
the attorney general said 
such a determination at this time is made especially difficult 
here by the breadth of the allegations and the fact that a number 
of figures central to the alleged conspiracy including secretary 
pierce and his executive assistant deborah dean have declined to 
be interviewed the attorney generals application said 
but thornburgh disclosed that pierce had provided written 
answers to questions the department submitted to him during the 
preliminary inquiry which began in dec 4 
ms dean also invoked the fifth amendment protection against 
selfincrimination in refusing to testify before the house 
subcommittee pierce also took the fifth when called back to 
testify last fall 
we will have no comment at this time until we have an 
opportunity to see the letter which of course we have not 
seen said joseph digenova who represents ms dean 
the attorney general noted that under the law he was barred from 
using the traditional prosecutorial tools such as issuing grand 
jury subpoenas or granting immunity to witnesses to conduct the 
preliminary inquiry 
nor was he able to base a decision to drop the investigation on 
a persons state of mind unless i can determine by clear and 
convincing evidence that the person lacked the requisite state of 
mind for criminal liability 
thornburgh said there was no reasonable basis to continue an 
investigation of the perjury allegations because the questioning by 
lawmakers and the answers pierce gave were too ambiguous 
the attorney general said pierces statement that he did not 
have hands on involvement in the award of moderate 
rehabilitation grants is fundamentally ambiguous which makes a 
perjury prosecution essentially impossible 
the terms is readily susceptible to countless 
interpretations thornburgh said 
rep tom lantos dcalif chairman of the subcommittee that 
investigated allegations of wrongdoing at hud said i welcome 
the attorney generals decision and believe that an independent 
counsel is in the best position to fully investigate and resolve 
questions of possible criminal wrongdoing 
rep bruce morrison dconn called thornburghs decision a 
very important step for those involved in the hud scandal to be 
held accountable by the criminal justice system 
morrison one of two judiciary committee members who pushed the 
drive for last falls congressional request said it was important 
that the independent counsel be authorized to pursue other 
officials too 
pierce was a new york lawyer before taking the secretarys post 
in 1981 plotkin declined to say what pierce is doing now 
 
</TEXT>
