residents of a neighborhood that was 
devastated by a train derailment and subsequent gas pipeline 
explosion sued southern pacific railroad and the pipeline company 
for negligence thursday 
the suit filed in superior court on behalf of 349 plaintiffs in 
san bernadino alleges negligence and conscious disregard of 
safety by the railroad and calnev pipe line co in the fatal 
accidents said attorney james h davis 
the amount sought for general compensatory and punitive damages 
was not specified davis said 
others named in the suit include the city and county of san 
bernardino the chairman of southern pacific and other individuals 
four people died and 30 were injured on may 12 1989 when a 
freight train roared out of control down a mountain pass and 
derailed throwing rail cars into the neighborhood 
brake failure and a flawed estimate of the load carried by the 
train contributed to the derailment according to testimony at 
federal hearings held last summer 
thirteen days after the derailment an underground fuel pipeline 
near the accident site exploded killing two people and injuring 31 
calnev had examined the pipeline which supplies 90 percent of 
las vegas gas after the derailment and declared it safe 
federal investigators have said they believe either the impact 
of the train accident or heavy equipment used to clean up debris 
from it weakened the buried pipeline ultimately causing it to 
explode 
however testimony during the hearings held by the national 
transportation safety board failed to establish a causal link 
between the two disasters an ntsb report on the hearings is 
pending 
most of the 90 families represented by the lawsuit lived on 
duffy and mcdonald streets davis said a total of nearly 20 homes 
were destroyed in the derailment and pipeline explosion and the 
area remains a total desert he said 
twenty years of my life ive lived there and it all went up 
