<TEXT>
a federal appeals court on wednesday 
reinstated a suit by a former los angeles prosecutor who claimed he 
was smeared after objecting to tactics in the twilight zone 
manslaughter case 
gary kesselman who was removed as prosecutor in the case 
against film director john landis sued los angeles deputy district 
attorney lea dagostino several supervisors and district attorney 
ira reiner for defamation wrongful firing and civil rights 
violations over disputes arising from the case 
us district judge dickran tevrizian had dismissed the suit on 
the grounds that the prosecutors were legally immune from suit 
even if kesselman could prove all of his allegations 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals disagreed wednesday 
returning the case to tevrizian for more pretrial proceedings 
landis and his codefendants were acquitted in 1987 of 
involuntary manslaughter in the deaths of actor vic morrow and two 
children on the twilight zone movie set in july 1982 
kesselman who was first assigned to prosecute the case said he 
was removed before the trial at his own request but a supervisor 
said he was removed for cause 
his suit involved testimony by a prosecution witness donna 
schuman that she had disclosed certain information to kesselman 
who had replied that he had planned to conceal it and spring it on 
the defense as a surprise kesselman denied the testimony and said 
she had never given her the information 
after that he said ms dagostino and supervisors in the 
office began a campaign to harass and discredit him 
kesselman now a private lawyer also contended he was fired 
from the office in retaliation for filing the suit the county 
denied it 
his dismissal came shortly after his arrest in 1987 for 
investigation of lewd conduct that case ended in a nocontest plea 
to disturbing the peace 
gregory petersen a lawyer for kesselman said he expected to 
prove that the prosecutor was fired for refusing to go along with 
the program of the offices approach to the case 
john collins a lawyer for the county and the prosecutors whom 
kesselman sued said he hoped the court would find them immune from 
suit for all matters related to presentation of evidence in the 
case 
