<TEXT>
a new suggests that combining an antibiotic with 
an overthecounter drug can reduce the duration of travelers 
diarrhea to just an hour from an average of 34 hours with the best 
known previous therapy 
we never dreamed it would work so well it was marvelous 
said dr charles d ericsson who with dr herbert l dupont led a 
team of researchers at the university of texas medical school at 
houston 
the researchers tested five different treatments including a 
placebo or inactive medication among 227 us college students 
who suffered from acute diarrhea while attending summer school in 
guadalajara mexico 
the quickest relief came from combining the antibiotic 
sulfamethoxazoletrimethoprim marketed as septra and bactrim with 
the overthecounter drug loperamide marketed as immodium ad the 
researchers said 
subjects took the antibiotic in tablet form twice a day for 
three days and an initial twotablet dose of loperamide ericsson 
said one additional tablet of loperamide was taken after each 
loose bowel movement 
the average duration of diarrhea was an hour or less with the 
combination of drugs vs 34 hours using the previous best therapy 
the antibiotic alone said ericsson in the control group the 
average duration was 59 hours 
less effective were the other three approaches tested a single 
large dose of the antibiotic twoaday doses of the antibiotic 
over three days and the overthecounter drug alone the 
researchers found their findings were reported in the journal of 
the american medical association 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
silicon microchips implanted into rats 
feet survived a year and linked with nerve tissue a step 
researchers say could in several decades lead to the development of 
bionic limbs 
the goal of this project is to make an interface a direct 
connection between the human nervous system and machines or 
prostheses said greg kovacs a stanford university electrical 
engineer and medical student 
two quartersized radio transceivers one at the stump of the 
severed part of the human body and connected to the chip and the 
other on the outside of the artificial limb could relay 
information by radio kovacs said 
the main challenge for scientists is being able to take the 
signals sent from the brain and interpret and process them into 
information that can be fed into the prosthesis circuits probably 
through a computer such a system is far in the future warned 
kovacs and three colleagues who last year implanted a tiny chip 
between the severed ends of foot nerves in a half dozen rats 
nerve fibers regenerated through holes in the chip and the 
researchers were eventually able to stimulate activity by sending 
signals through the chip 
kovacs said the holes in the chips were small enough that only 
single nerves or small clusters grew in each pathway the chips 
probably will not be useful in reconnecting severed limbs or other 
body parts he said because of the irreversible damage generally 
caused by the cutting 
</TEXT>
