<TEXT>
intrigued by stories of two dogs who reportedly 
could sense that their masters were about to have epileptic 
seizures researchers are looking for other dogs who appear to have 
that ability 
if dogs can be trained to give warnings they might make life 
easier for people with epilepsy by giving them time to take 
precautions to avoid injury during the seizure said reina berner 
executive director of the epilepsy institute in new york 
as a result some people with epilepsy could become less fearful 
of having seizures in public and so begin to lead less restricted 
lives she said 
the institute hopes to find three to five dogs who appear to 
have the ability so the animals can be formally tested if it 
appears researchers hope to find out how they do it so other dogs 
can be trained berner said 
the testing would involve monitoring brain waves of a volunteer 
to watch for the signal of an impending seizure and noting if and 
when the dog senses the seizure coming 
berner said she had heard of one dog in washington dc who 
could sense seizures in a girl and had met a second such dog and 
its owner the owner said that while she was taking a shower the 
dog had predicted an oncoming seizure by barking even though the 
animal was outside the closed bathroom door 
both dogs had been trained to work for people using wheelchairs 
she said in addition both appeared able to predict not only grand 
mal seizures which make a person collapse but also complex 
partial seizures in which a person becomes semiconcious and 
lapses into such simple behavior as walking 
</TEXT>
