<TEXT>
treasury secretary nicholas brady today urged 
congress to adopt the presidents proposed taxfree family savings 
account as a way to boost americas competitive standing in global 
markets 
brady appearing before the senate budget committee to promote 
the tax aspects of the presidents 1991 budget request said the 
administration felt strongly that the new savings accounts along 
with a proposed cut in the capital gains tax would foster the 
longterm investment needed by us businesses to stay competitive 
an important goal for the 1990s is to increase the rate of 
growth of americas productive capacity brady said more 
saving is needed to finance increases in our productive capacity 
we believe that the federal government should foster an environment 
that is conducive to saving and we have a plan to achieve this 
objective 
the family savings account which bush mentioned in his state of 
the union address would allow an individual taxpayer to save up to 
2500 a year and a family to invest up to 5000 a year with the 
money earning interest taxfree as long as it was held for at least 
seven years 
the administration sees this proposal as the centerpiece of an 
effort to increase personal savings rates and thus expand the pool 
of money available for businesses to borrow to modernize production 
facilities 
senate budget committee chairman james sasser dtenn however 
questioned both the savings proposal and the administrations 
renewed effort to cut the capital gains tax saying that both 
measures would lose revenue at a time when the government was still 
facing massive federal deficits 
sasser said the family savings account would provide only a 
minimal increase in private savings while costing the government 
tax revenues 
also appearing before the committee today was michael boskin 
the presidents chief economic adviser both boskin and brady 
defended the bush budget against charges that it relied heavily on 
overly optimistic economic forecasts to reach the required deficit 
target for 1991 
in earlier testimony before the house budget committee boskin 
said the economy is now going through a sluggish period with 
economic growth as measured by the gross national product 
dropping to a barely perceptible 05 percent annual rate in the 
final three months of 1989 
boskin said that although he expects growth to pick up modestly 
in the first three months of this year another quarter of growth 
below 1 percent is possible 
under the grammrudman deficit reduction law two consecutive 
quarters of growth below 1 percent would require lawmakers to vote 
on suspending the deficit reduction targets for 1991 
boskin urged lawmakers not to do so especially if the economy 
is showing signs of an imminent rebound 
a suspension of grammrudman could have very unfavorable 
impacts on financial markets and cause interest rates to rise 
boskin said in testimony wednesday 
budget director richard darman denied the budget ignores the 
movement toward democracy in eastern europe which many lawmakers 
view as requiring less pentagon spending than the 292 billion 
proposed by the administration 
the reality is that this is a budget which proposes a 26 
percent real cut in military spending after taking account of 
inflation in the first year and a 2 percent real cut every year 
thereafter darman said 
robert d reischauer head of the bipartisan congressional 
budget office said the cbo came up with a 37 billion higher 
deficit for the 1991 fiscal year than the bush administration is 
assuming 
cbo put the 1991 deficit at 138 billion without any changes in 
current policy compared with the 101 billion claimed by the 
administration 
reischauer said more than twothirds of the higher cbo figure 
26 billion was a direct result of less optimistic forecasts on 
economic growth and interest rates the other 11 billion came from 
higher expected spending for the savings and loan bailout and such 
programs as medicare 
because of its assumptions the administration needed just 37 
billion in savings to meet the requirement of proposing a budget 
with a 64 billion deficit in the 1991 budget year which starts in 
october down from an expected deficit this year of 1238 billion 
but reischauer said the cbo assumptions would double the amount 
of savings needed by the administration 
congress may adopt either the cbo estimate or the assumptions in 
the bush budget in drawing up its own spending plan but the 
administrations assumptions must be used later in the year in 
determining whether acrosstheboard spending cuts are needed to 
meet the deficit target 
</TEXT>
