<TEXT>
japans fair trade commission said thursday its 
international committee was considering applying antimonopoly 
regulations to all foreign companies whose business practices 
affect japan 
japans current antimonopoly law applies only to japanese 
companies and subsidiaries of foreign firms operating within japan 
commission spokesman kazutoshi fujishiro said the commissions 
international committee was to report by midfebruary on the 
feasibility of extending the law to other foreign companies 
the 15member committee was set up two years ago because of the 
increasingly global scale of business activities he added 
fujishiro said small adjustments in some related laws and 
consultation with foreign countries would be needed to extend the 
the reach of japans antimonopoly law beyond its borders 
the newspaper yomiuri shimbun said the commission a watchdog 
body to ensure fair business competition would soon begin 
fullscale preparations for revision of the antimonopoly law 
the revision would indirectly contribute to bringing down the 
high prices of imported goods in japan it said 
the paper said other nations also extend the reach of their 
antimonopoly laws beyond national borders 
</TEXT>
