<TEXT>
major us retailers today reported fair sales gains in january 
with some having better luck than others clearing out leftover 
holiday merchandise 
sales at stores open at least a year rose around 5 percent 
industrywide from a year earlier according to estimates by retail 
analysts 
chains specializing in apparel had the best growth while mass 
merchandisers including the nations two largest retailers sears 
roebuck and co and k mart corp tallied increases below the 
industry average 
january is typically a slow time in the retailing trade and the 
month marks the end of the fiscal year for many merchants 
consumers usually have had their fill of spending at christmas and 
some people enter the new year bearing credit card debts that 
discourage them from shopping for awhile 
widespread price cutting and other promotions this past holiday 
season particularly by debtladen department stores desperate to 
raise cash may have left buyers more bloated than usual 
edward johnson a retail analyst at prescott ball amp turben inc 
said the first three weeks of january were sluggish for retailers 
as consumers nursed a bad case of postchristmas spending blues 
but shoppers began returning to stores in the last week of the 
month 
the seasonally adjusted pace of sales quickened in the final 
week to about 85 percent from 48 percent in the first three 
weeks he said 
jeffrey edelman of drexel burnham lambert inc said retailers 
that had the leanest inventories due to brisk holiday business 
generally had the lowest january sales gains the ones stuck with 
excess after christmas pushed hard to move the merchandise to make 
room for spring lines and therefore posted higher sales results 
looking ahead jeffrey feiner a merrill lynch amp co analyst 
said an erosion in consumer confidence lately reflecting 
uncertainty about economic conditions and weakness in financial 
markets portends tougher times for retailers 
weakness in both the housing and financial markets makes the 
outlook for consumer spending in retail stores in our opinion 
likely to be quite sluggish at least over the near term feiner 
said 
the sales reports today were from general merchandise chains 
department stores specialty apparel retailers and others here are 
some of the results 
sears the nations biggest retailer said sales rose 22 
percent in the four weeks ended jan 27 to 217 billion from 212 
billion a year earlier sales at stores open at least a year 
called same or comparablestore sales rose 33 percent 
analysts and store executives attach greater significance to 
samestore tallies because the excitement of new store openings can 
inflate sales temporarily providing distorted results 
k mart second in size to sears reported a 131 percent 
increase in sales to 179 billion from 158 billion but on a 
samestore basis sales were up 31 percent 
no 3ranked walmart stores inc which typically outperforms 
rival discounters said sales grew 24 percent to 184 billion from 
148 billion excluding newly opened stores sales rose 10 percent 
among retailers concentrating on apparel jc penney co inc 
said sales increased 85 percent to 779 million from 718 mllion a 
year earlier samestore sales rose 73 percent 
the specialty apparel retailer the limited inc posted an 11 
percent sales increase to 2856 million from 2567 million while 
sales grew 9 percent on a comparable store basis 
the gap inc another clothing specialist said january sales 
surged 34 percent to 94 million from the year earliers 70 
million samestore sales jumped 24 percent 
dayton hudson corp owner of department stores and the large 
target discount chain said january sales went up 122 percent to 
711 million from 634 million sales at stores open at least a 
year rose 52 percent 
woolworth corp owner of fw woolworth co stores plus 
numerous specialty retailers including the foot locker chain said 
domestic january sales rose 85 percent to 283 million from 261 
million domestic sales were up 45 percent at stores open for a 
year or more 
</TEXT>
