<TEXT>
sci television inc avoided being placed under 
federal bankrupcty court protection after a judge in delaware 
approved a lastminute change in the companys debt revision plan 
a lawyer for sci said 
the company now faces a new deadline of monday to complete a 
restructuring of its 13 billion debt 
the denverbased operator of six television stations unable to 
meet interest payments on its debt has been trying to get 
bondholders to accept stock and securities in exchange for their 
507 million in outstanding bonds 
as part of its planned debt restructuring the company specified 
that certain minimum levels of each of three series of bonds must 
be tendered under its exchange offer the requirement already had 
been met on two series of bonds but sci remained short of the 
minimum acceptance level of 875 percent for a third issue 
the company faced a deadline of 430 pm est wednesday to 
certify that it had been tendered or promised at least 875 percent 
of its 100 million issue of 16 percent senior subordinated 
debentures or be placed under bankruptcy protection 
as the deadline approached sci lawyer james l patton jr said 
the company requested that the minimum acceptance level be reduced 
to 85 percent and the judge agreed sci was able to certify that 
it had met the reduced minimum 
but in a statement today the company said that a closer 
examination of the tenders and promises to tender showed that there 
had been some miscounts of tenders received and the nontender of 
securities which sci understood had been offered to be tendered 
and that it had been tendered only 832 percent of the bonds as of 
this morning 
as a result it said the court was informed and has taken no 
action to modify or rescind its previous orders 
sci said it was holding the exchange offer open until noon est 
friday in an effort to get the required 85 percent of the bonds 
the company has been unable to generate enough cash to meet 
payments due on 13 billion in debt incurred when it was acquired 
in 1987 by the entrepreneur george gillett and a group led by the 
buyout specialists kohlberg kravis roberts amp co 
gillett owns 55 percent of sci while the kohlberg group owns the 
rest 
under the debt restructuring plan the bondholders will get a 39 
percent equity stake in the company and bank lenders will get 5 
percent gilletts stake will be trimmed to 41 percent and 
kohlbergs stake to 15 percent 
sci television operates stations wsbk in boston wjbk in 
detroit wjw in cleveland waga in atlanta knsd in san diego and 
witi in milwaukee 
