<TEXT>
construction spending advanced last year at 
its slowest pace since the 1982 recession the government said 
thursday analysts blamed the weakness on high interest rates 
overbuilding and a sluggish economy 
the commerce department said residential nonresidential and 
government construction spending totaled 4147 billion a 12 
percent increase over 1988 but the smallest gain since a 51 
percent decline in 1982 
contributing to the poor showing was a 06 percent decline in 
december spending which was buffeted by record cold weather over 
most of the country east of the rockies 
spending totaled a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4146 
billion in december nearly erasing a 07 percent gain in november 
it was the lowest onemonth increase since a decline of 1 percent 
last june 
analysts said federal reserve actions that kept interest rates 
relatively high through most of the year not only made construction 
more expensive but also slowed the economy and thus made sales 
more difficult 
plus you had a number of good years of construction leading 
up to 1989 said david berson chief economist for the federal 
national mortgage association eventually you have all the 
houses and office buildings that you need you run out of pentup 
demand 
because of the lessening demand and the state of the economy 
berson said 1990 at best will be about what it was in 1989 and 
could even fall a little bit 
another factor beginning to worry builders and analysts alike is 
the adverse effect of the savings and loan bailout law on the 
availability of construction financing 
the law limits the amount that savings and loans can lend to 
any one construction company said economist steven cochran of 
wefa group in bala cynwyd pa who added that efforts are under 
way to resolve the problem 
analysts point to widespread vacancies in office buildings as 
evidence of overbuilding in the nonresidential sector which 
continued to grow last year 
nonresidential spending was up 24 percent to 994 billion in 
1989 and 43 percent to an annual rate of 967 billion in december 
residential spending representing 50 percent of construction 
spending was off 11 percent to 1959 billion last year and down 
07 percent in december to an annual rate of 191 billion 
but singlefamily construction picked up 04 percent to an 
annual rate of 1443 billion in december the third straight 
advance after falling for eight months multifamily spending 
which has fallen every month since july was down 28 percent to a 
206 billion annual rate 
the usually volatile government sector rose 38 percent to 84 
billion in 1989 and 29 percent to a 911 billion annual rate in 
december when it was boosted by a 93 percent gain in highway and 
street projects government projects account for about 20 percent 
of construction spending 
</TEXT>
