<TEXT>
the us economy fell sharply in january for the 
ninth consecutive month and at the greatest rate of decline since 
the last recession the nations purchasing managers said thursday 
in a widely watched survey 
the monthly report which substantiated other evidence of an 
economic slowdown contributed to a downward blip in stock trading 
early in the day but it didnt last analysts said it had little 
effect on bond trading 
david wyss an economist for the forecasting firm 
drimcgrawhill inc said the financial markets were too busy 
worrying about the state of the union address last night 
the markets were preoccupied with the implications of president 
bushs proposals wednesday night for troop reductions in europe 
which could lead to a lower federal deficit and in turn lower 
interest rates wyss said 
alan levenson an economist for salomon brothers inc said the 
purchasing survey result was about what the markets expected so 
the reaction was not unusual 
the national association of purchasing management said its 
monthly index fell in january to 452 percent down from 467 
percent in december 
a reading below 50 indicates that the us manufacturing economy 
is declining while above 50 indicates expansion the group said 
the index has been below 50 for the past nine months 
the figures were adjusted to reflect an update of the seasonal 
adjustment factors of the us commerce department that are used to 
calculate the index 
it confirms what weve been saying and whats been obvious for 
a while which is that the economy is slowing down rather 
dramatically wyss said but we dont see signs of recession 
wyss pointed out that a key part of the survey supplier 
deliveries was up in january to 472 percent from 425 percent in 
december the figure shows how fast companies receive goods they 
order an increase means supplier companies are operating at a 
higher capacity 
wyss said this figure is important because it is a component of 
the commerce departments monthly leading indicators the 
governments chief economic forecasting gauge 
however the purchasing group attributed the increase to fewer 
weatherrelated delays in producing and transporting goods 
the groups new export orders figure also continued to show 
relative strength said the group based in tempe ariz the 
seasonally unadjusted export orders index increased to 555 percent 
from 53 percent in december 
the new orders portion of the groups survey fell significantly 
in january the employment component declined for the 11th 
consecutive month and the inventories index was the lowest since 
1986 
the manufacturing economy entered 1990 on a dismal note 
said robert j bretz chairman of the groups survey committee he 
said it was the greatest rate of decline since december 1982 when 
the nation was starting to pull out of the last recession 
he said the groups overall monthly index averaged 489 percent 
for all of 1989 that figure is consistent with real gross national 
product growth of about 22 percent after adding 06 percent to 
reflect the rebound in agricultural output last year from the 1988 
drought he said 
bretz said the index would have to fall below 44 percent before 
it indicates a decline in real gnp 
doug handler an economist for dun amp bradstreet corp said the 
report was weaker than he expected but that other recent 
statistics show the economys manufacturing sector is bottoming 
out in general 
the survey is based on responses from executives who buy goods 
at more than 300 industrial companies 
</TEXT>
