<DOCNO> AP900201-0278 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in seeking to entice americans to save more 
money the white house is tackling a job that has been an 
overwhelming challenge to other american institutions including 
motherhood 
it begins with parents exhorting youngsters to put pennies in a 
piggy bank the lesson is developed throughout schooling the 
challenge is then taken on by banks by companies with payroll 
savings plans and by others 
to some degree all have failed which is why the bush 
administration now wants to attack the problem with tax 
enticements promising not to levy a penny against certain savings 
accounts left to build and age 
savings it is sometimes contended are the reason the japanese 
have gained such economic prominence their high savings rate 15 
percent to 20 percent of income sometimes more finances swift 
industrial expansion 
but using the japanese as a model or european nations which 
recently have saved at a rate double that of americans might not 
work americans are very different people with very different 
habits and approaches to life 
in the past 60 years the only time in which the american 
savings rate came close to recent japanese levels was when 
literally they were forced to save during world war ii payrolls 
were big but there was little to buy 
at the time some officials thought they had stumbled on a truth 
that savings bonds issued by the government and carrying the full 
faith and credit of uncle sam had something to do with it but the 
program faded after the war 
the savings binge ended in fact with the war in the five 
years 19411945 the rate averaged better than 20 percent in 1946 
it dived to 85 percent and the following year to 31 percent 
lower than the current level 
except for those years there has never been a doubledigit 
savings rate the amount saved as a percent of disposable or 
aftertax income the rate has moved up and down but the highest 
was 94 percent in 1973 
moreover the reasons for fluctuations arent entirely clear 
some of the evidence even contradicts pet theories such as that 
economic stability encourages savings 
that wasnt true in the early 1970s when inflation ran wild on 
average the first six years of that decade had the highest savings 
rate of any similar since the 1940s in 1974 the rate reached 93 
percent inflation 10 percent 
that is the second highest oneyear savings rate since world 
war ii was accompanied by the first doubledigit inflation rate in 
modern times it was a tragedy for savers since inflation exceeded 
the rate of interest earned 
it was in the early 1980s that concern steadily mounted in 
1983 the rate dipped to just 54 percent and to 44 percent in 
1985 and from then until last year it remained under 5 percent 
that decline is now seized upon by those who link it to the rise 
in federal budget deficits they could be correct in fact when 
evidence developed last year that it was possible to cut the 
deficit the rate rose above 5 percent 
while the budgetdeficit link might seem a strong one there is 
another school of thought economist edward yardeni and others see 
a connection with an entirely different set of figures demographic 
ones 
according to them the reason for low savings rates since the 
early and mid1980s is the bulge of younger people working its way 
through the economy 
as these people get older and put their bigspending years 
behind them says yardeni they will become savers content to sit 
on the couch and watch television instead of renting cars for ski 
weekends and other entertainment 
there are still more theories 
one thesis is that americans have pensions social security and 
large equity in homes and so have a sense of security that allows 
them to forego saving as narrowly defined 
another why save if inflation is just going to wipe it out 
another in view of recent shenanigans why entrust savings to 
banks and savings and loan associations that will only spend it 
their way 
one more who has money to save 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

