<TEXT>
drexel burnham lambert inc agreed to pay 
massachusetts 1 million in a settlement announced thursday the 
latest settlement arising from the wall street firms guilty plea 
to securities fraud charges 
massachusetts became the 41st state to reach such an agreement 
with drexel the amount was the largest settlement ever paid to the 
state in a securities matter according to secretary of state 
michael j connolly 
drexel pleaded guilty last september in us district court in 
new york to six felonies and paid 650 million to settle a range of 
fraud allegations stemming from the governments lengthy 
investigation of insider trading on wall street 
drexel also agreed to dozens of administrative changes and 
unprecedented federal supervision in settling civil charges with 
the securities and exchange commission 
under the settlement with the federal government drexel paid 
300 million in fines to the government and set aside 350 million 
for investors who can prove they were harmed by the firms actions 
those who may be entitled to restitution include people who bought 
stocks in about 20 allegedly fraudulent transactions cited by the 
sec 
the settlement with massachusetts is one of the largest the firm 
has reached with states so far drexel paid illinois about 12 
million and missouri announced a 1 million settlement on wednesday 
with the massachusetts agreement drexel has paid states 
settlements totaling 83 million 
were pleased we were able to settle it and now we can go 
about our business said steven anreder a drexel spokesman 
the 1 million settlement will go into the states general fund 
connolly said 
connolly said the 275000 originally offered by the firm was 
inadequate 
settling with the states relieves drexel of possible litigation 
and frees state regulators from having to investigate the firms 
trading activities from 1984 to 1986 when the sec alleged the 
fraud occurred 
the settlements also generally preserve the firms ability to 
underwrite securities and do other business in the states most 
states can revoke a companys right to do business if the firm is 
convicted or admits to committing a felony drexel abandoned the 
retail stock brokerage business last year 
in massachusetts the agreement includes a stipulation that 
drexel must not solicit any new retail trade without first 
notifying the state securities division and demonstrating that 
compliance procedures are in place 
the firm also cannot sponsor private placements to individuals 
and must work with the securities division to identify any state 
investors injured by the illegal sale of drexel junk bonds victims 
would be entitled to place claims with the 350 million 
compensation fund drexel established 
in addition drexel must hire an independent consultant to 
scrutinize company policies and submit compliance reports hire an 
ombudsman to receive and investigate complaints finance annual 
audits by the state securities division and establish an oversight 
committee to review its internal procedures 
connolly said he did not know whether any massachusetts 
residents were hurt by drexel sales 
drexel has been working with state regulators for the past eight 
months and connolly said officials monitoring the firm during that 
time have given them high marks 
</TEXT>
