<TEXT>
the chairman of a senate panel said thursday 
that he wants to hold hearings into the jurisdictional dispute 
between the securities and exchange commission and the agency that 
regulates the futures industry 
im fully aware of the hornets nest one can hit here said 
sen christopher j dodd dconn about possible opposition from 
farm area congressmen who oversee the commodity futures trading 
commission 
a longsimmering rivalry between the sec which regulates the 
stock and bond markets and the cftc which oversees the nations 
futures markets heated up last year when a federal appeals court 
ruled in favor of the cftc 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals held that financial 
products that contain any aspects of a futures contract should be 
regulated by the cftc not the sec 
sec chairman richard c breeden who testified before dodds 
securities subcommittee of the senate banking housing and urban 
affairs committee thursday has been very vocal about resolving the 
dispute which he says is driving new financial products out of the 
country 
we are the only country in the world that has a separate 
agency to regulate the cash market and the derivative market 
breeden said in response to a question by dodd 
i would very much like to see us debate this issue in this 
congress said dodd i realize its one that will raise some 
feathers in certain quarters but it needs to be addressed 
the subcommittees ranking republican sen john heinz of 
pennsylvania said he supported dodds suggestion for a public 
airing of the issue 
in the past members of committees in both the house and senate 
have been careful not to tred outside their bailiwick as a sign of 
professional courtesy and political expediency despite occasional 
calls to resolve the dispute 
it is still a critical issue said heinz we shouldnt be 
deterred from examining even the most fearful subject politically 
fearful in this case 
heinz added that he hoped dodd will brave the wasps hornets 
and spiders and probably a few snakes as well that are likely 
to crawl out of the woodwork 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals in chicago last summer 
ruled that the sec overstepped its authority in authorizing three 
securities exchanges it regulates to trade in a hybrid financial 
instrument known as a stock basket 
technically called an index participation the product 
resembles a basket of stocks because it allows investors to buy or 
sell something with a value tied to broad stock market indexes 
such as the standard amp poors 500 
but the appeals court held that such products come under the 
cftcs supervision if they have any element of a futures product 
the appeals court refused to rehear the secs arguments and now 
its up to the solicitor general to decide if the dispute should be 
brought before the us supreme court for a possible hearing 
we would defend our exclusive jurisdiction at the same time 
it doesnt mean were against innovative products a cftc 
spokesman said in a telephone interview 
wed like to see some alternative worked out without 
litigation there are a lot of ramifications that have to be 
carefully considered said the spokesman who asked not to be 
named 
</TEXT>
