<TEXT>
centel cellular telephone co has agreed to 
pay 1 million to the government over a 1989 accident in which two 
people died when their helicopter crashed into a radio tower under 
construction in north carolina a federal communications commission 
official said thursday 
chicagobased centel which is not admitting any liability in 
the accident also will conduct a 2year educational safety 
awareness campaign within the cellular industry on antenna marking 
and lighting as part of an fccapproved consent decree said greg 
vogt chief of the commissions mobile services division 
the consent decree resolves an fcc complaint that centel 
allegedly had failed to comply with fcc requirements for tower 
marking and lighting 
the consent decree stemmed from a 1989 collision of a medivac 
helicopter with a tower at coinjock nc that was owned by a 
centel subsidiary the commission said two people in the 
helicopter were killed 
following an investigation of that accident and another 1989 
incident involving a centel tower in portsmouth va the fccs 
field operations bureau cited centel for possibly violating fcc 
rules 
vogt said the consent decree which was issued tuesday 
resolves any pending sanctions that we might impose on centel for 
the violation of our rules 
however centel will have to pay 1 million within five days and 
conduct an education campaign within the industry to make sure 
other licensees know their obligations to light towers during 
construction vogt said 
there has been some concern at the commission that licensees 
havent been diligent enough to make sure their lights are on and 
working both during construction and afterwards he said 
two civil suits claiming wrongful deaths also were filed in the 
north carolina case vogt said 
</TEXT>
