followed a similar 350 million charge the bank took in the third 
quarter for losses at its arizona bank 
last week first interstate reported a fourthquarter loss of 
3443 million because of problems at the texas bank the former 
allied bancshares which first interstate acquired in early 1988 
first interstate revealed the sec inquiry in a filing related to 
its plan to issue 75 million new shares of stock to bolster its 
capital which was depleted by the writedown 
the wall street journal said the inquiry likely was aimed at 
exploring whether first interstate had violated disclosure laws by 
not reporting its texas problems more promptly 
the journal also reported that federal regulators have placed 
first interstates arizona unit under strict supervisory controls 
and that first interstate may need regulatory approval to continue 
paying its 75 cent quarterly dividend 
the banks filing also contained a warning that the big losses 
may not be over 
as a consequence of general economic conditions in the 
operating regions of the corporations subsidiary banks 
particularly the southwest united states however there can be no 
assurance that further substantial additions to the corporations 
allowance for loan losses will not be required the filing said 
first interstate is the nations 10th largest bank holding 
company with 58 billion in assets the bank has been trying to cut 
costs through layoffs and selling businesses outside of its core 
consumer and business banking divisions because of the arizona and 
texas losses 
